sols:
As there are constants and exponentials in this first-order linear ODE,
we will use undetermined coefficients, postulating that the particular
solution is

$x_p(t) = \left(\begin{array}{c}
B_1 \\ B_2
\end{array}\right) e^{2t} + \left(\begin{array}{c}
C_1 \\ C_2
\end{array}\right).$

so that

$x_p' (t) = \left(\begin{array}{c}
2 B_1 \\ 2 B_2
\end{array}\right) e^{2t}.$

Substituting our solution into the system we get,

\begin{align*}
&Ax +
\begin{pmatrix}
-2 e^{2t} \\ 1
\end{pmatrix}\\
&=
\begin{pmatrix}
3  &  1\\
-4  &  -1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
B_1e^{2t}+C_1\\
B_2e^{2t}+C_2
\end{pmatrix}
+ \begin{pmatrix}
-2 e^{2t} \\ 1
\end{pmatrix}\\
&=
\begin{pmatrix}
3B_1 + B_2 - 2 \\ -4 B_1 -  B_2
\end{pmatrix} e^{2t}
+ \begin{pmatrix}
3 C_1 + C_2 \\ -4 C_1 - C_2 +1
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

This must equal $\displaystyle{}x_p'$ and so we have

\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix}
3B_1 + B_2 - 2 \\ -4 B_1 -  B_2
\end{pmatrix} e^{2t}
+ \begin{pmatrix}
3 C_1 + C_2 \\ -4 C_1 - C_2 +1
\end{pmatrix}
&=
\begin{pmatrix}
2B_1\\
2B_2
\end{pmatrix}e^{2t}\\
\begin{pmatrix}
B_1 + B_2 - 2 \\ -4 B_1 -  3 B_2
\end{pmatrix} e^{2t}
+ \begin{pmatrix}
3 C_1 + C_2 \\ -4 C_1 - C_2 +1
\end{pmatrix}
&=\mathbf{0}
\end{align*}

This gives us the system of equations

\begin{align*} B_1 + B_2 - 2 &= 0 \\ -4 B_1 - 3 B_2 &= 0 \end{align*}

(based on the $e^{2t}$ terms)

and

\begin{align*} 3C_1 + C_2 &= 0 \\ -4 C_1 - C_2 &= -1 \end{align*}

(based on comparing the constant vectors).

Looking at the first equation of the first system of equations, we have
$B_1 = 2 - B_2$ so that in the second equation,

\begin{align*}
-4(2 - B_2) - 3 B_2 &= 0\\
B_2 &= 8.
\end{align*}

Using the first equation again, we get

\[\displaystyle{}B_1 = -6.\]

Looking at the first equation of the second system of equations, we have
$C_2 = -3 C_1$. From the second equation we get

\begin{align*}
-4C_1 - (-3 C_1) &= -1\\
C_1& = 1.
\end{align*}

and hence

\[\displaystyle{}C_2 = -3\]

after substituting back into the first equation.

The general solution to the ODE system will be $u_p + u_h$ where $u_h$
is our homogeneous solution from
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH215/December_2011/Question_6_(b)}{part
(b)}.

Thus,

\[x(t) =
\begin{pmatrix}
1 \\ -3
\end{pmatrix}
+
\begin{pmatrix}
-6 \\ 8
\end{pmatrix}e^{2t}
+
\begin{pmatrix}
ct e^t + b e^t \\ -2 ct e^t + (c-2b)e^t
\end{pmatrix}.\]

If

\[\displaystyle{}x(0) = (1, -5)^T\]

then

\[\begin{pmatrix}
1\\
-5
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1 - 6 + b\\
-3 + 8 + (c-2b))
\end{pmatrix}.\]

The first component tells us that $b = 6$ while using this value of b in
the second component gives $c = 2$.

Therefore, the solution is

$x(t) = \left(\begin{array}{c}
1 \\ -3
\end{array}\right) + \left(\begin{array}{c}
-6 \\ 8
\end{array}\right) e^{2t} + \left(\begin{array}{c}
2t e^t + 6 e^t \\ -4 t e^t - 10 e^t
\end{array}\right).$
